<div id="review_1316644006" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1316644006" />
    <a title="B. P. Rinehart" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4635205-b-p-rinehart"><img alt="B. P. Rinehart" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1347740735p2/4635205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1316644006?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="B. P. Rinehart" class="user" itemprop="url" name="B. P. Rinehart" href="/user/show/4635205-b-p-rinehart">B. P. Rinehart</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/19806938-the-autobiography-of-malcolm-x">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4635205-b-p-rinehart?shelf=biography">biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4635205-b-p-rinehart?shelf=non-fiction-stuff">non-fiction-stuff</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1316644006" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12129851166679494119">&quot;<i>I&apos;m telling it like it <u>is</u>! You <u>never</u> have to worry about me biting my tongue if something I know as truth is on my mind. Raw, naked truth exchanged between the black man and the white man is what a whole lot more of is needed in this country-to clear the air of racial mirages, clichés, and lies that this country&apos;s very atmosphere has been filled with for four hundred years.</i><br/><br/>The man, legend, myth--El Hajj Malik el-Shabazz. To talk about the book itself first. This autobiography is one of the best</span>
  <span id="freeText12129851166679494119" style="display:none">"<i>I'm telling it like it <u>is</u>! You <u>never</u> have to worry about me biting my tongue if something I know as truth is on my mind. Raw, naked truth exchanged between the black man and the white man is what a whole lot more of is needed in this country-to clear the air of racial mirages, clichés, and lies that this country's very atmosphere has been filled with for four hundred years.</i><br /><br />The man, legend, myth--El Hajj Malik el-Shabazz. To talk about the book itself first. This autobiography is one of the best written that I have read and the credit goes to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/17434.Alex_Haley" title="Alex Haley" rel="nofollow noopener">Alex Haley</a> who was the one who recorded and edited the autobiography himself. Haley had met with Malcolm X 50+ times between 1963 and February 1965--and after Shabazz's assassination, he rushed to get this book released. It is easily the most readable book, fiction or non-fiction, I have ever read. The long musings of Malcolm X are cleanly placed together with his recollections and make for compelling reading, whatever your feelings of the content. Of course, this is just the editing process, what about the content?<br /><br />If I can say what I think Malcolm X taught me and most generations of African-Americans that have come after him is self-love--he taught Black people how to love themselves. I had not really thought about it before (despite being born in the height of the Malcolm X revival of the late 1980s to early 1990s). It was not until I read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/464260.The_Fire_Next_Time" title="The Fire Next Time by James Baldwin" rel="nofollow noopener">The Fire Next Time</a> that I really sat back and thought about this and realized this was the case. Malcolm X's words described so accurately a very uniquely African-American experience. The stages of this book were dictated as Malcolm X was evolving and his narrative evolves along with it. His rhetoric in his pre-Mecca days are like the songs of a Siren to Black people of the post-civil rights generations (and like Odysseus, I have to use my better sense of morals--like restraints--to keep from being seduced) because of his ability to plainly state the truth of what happened in the past and to clearly analyze the problems of race in the current day; what Malcolm X's fallacy was a lack of credible solutions to racism. I think the best parts of the book deal with his transition from the NOI (Nation of Islam) to Sunni Islam during his Hajj to Mecca.<br /><br />It cannot be emphasized enough how much his pilgrimage changed him and how he thought about race. It is the first time he saw what true human sympathy and love--regardless of race--looked like. His description of the whole process, of getting into Saudi Arabia, getting into Mecca and Medina, officially converting, and going through all the rituals of the Hajj, and finally realizing that there are blonde-haired, blue-eyed people who did genuinely sympathize with the plight of Black people, changed him. He personally became convinced that if all people in America embraced Islam it could dramatically solve "the race problem" in America. While, that does not seem to be a possibility in today's America it does illustrate in the book, when you compare it with previous chapters, how far he had come in his life. <blockquote>"<i>The color-blindness of the Muslim world's religious society and the color-blindness of the Muslim world's human society: these two influences had each day been making a greater impact, and an increasing persuasion against my previous way of thinking.</i>"</blockquote>If this book is to be read for anything, it is to be read for an examination how a great man can be transformed to a greater man. <br /><br />The often repeated motif of Malcolm X's life is transformation or evolution. He never stopped, and convinced those around him to never stop. I will never forget listening to <a href="http://video.pbs.org/video/1385340925/" rel="nofollow noopener">a debate between Malcolm X and some of the leaders of CORE and the SCLC</a> that took place the day after Medgar Evers was assassinated. When a retrospective interview was held with debaters still living (at the end of the video), they did not hesitate to say that while they continue to reject violence, Malcolm X was very accurate in diagnosing the short-comings of interaction and the subsequent decades had confirmed much of what X had predicted--to their dismay. This is, for me at least, the best evidence we have of why Malcolm X remains a very relevant voice in today's society.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12129851166679494119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

